english:
  title: Inscription on the Bamboo Window
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A hermit from Three Peaks came upon Master Lee, known as Yeon-chang, and asked: "Is it true, sir, that your name is Bamboo Window? Bamboo has a hollow heart and straight joints, and its color does not fade through winter's freeze. This is why gentlemen revere it to strengthen their resolve. In the Classics too, bamboo inspires the natural beauty of a gentleman's character and the progress of his learning—surely the meaning runs deep. Ancient worthies drew much from bamboo, so I dare ask what drew you to it."

    The Master replied: "No grand philosophy here. Simply this: in spring, birds nest in bamboo, their songs ring clear and bright. In summer, the wind stirs it, and its spirit turns fresh and cool. In autumn and winter, snow and moonlight grace it, its form spare and elegant. From morning dew to evening mist, from noon shadows to night's whisper—all that reaches ear and eye carries not a speck of worldly dust. Here I rise early, wash myself, sit before this window in stillness, burn incense, read, or play the zither. At times I cast aside ten thousand thoughts and sit in silent repose, forgetting even that my body dwells in this bamboo room."

    Ah, the Master's joy lives not in the bamboo itself, but in a peace of heart merely reflected through it. Let this be my inscription:

    Open the window, and dense bamboo appears—
    the dwelling place of gentlemen, whose virtue gleams like jade.
    To left and right, books rest waiting;
    each dawn and dusk I turn their pages.
    Unswayed by things, I taste this joy alone.
  footnotes:
    - 'Three Peaks (三峯): A reference to a famous mountain or perhaps a poetic pseudonym for the hermit questioner.'
    - The closing verses shift from prose dialogue to a formal inscription in verse, a common structure in East Asian literary tradition, moving from explanation to crystallized wisdom.
